    <h1>Protecting the Loop</h1>
    <p class="text-gray-400 text-sm mb-6">Chapter 12 &middot; Bacon 1620, Peirce 1878, Popper 1934, Meehl 1967, Feynman 1974, Ramdas 2023</p>

    <div class="bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg p-5 mb-8 callout">
      <p class="text-lg" style="max-width:none">An agent runs the hypothesis graph and "confirms" every hypothesis. It abduced from the data and tested on the same data. Peirce's question 9. Part IV begins here: the framework works mathematically. Can it run without a human?</p>
    </div>

    <p>Part III proved convergence. E-values compose. Kill conditions generate edges. The hypothesis graph closes when every open edge resolves. The machinery is sound. Hand it to an autonomous agent and watch what happens.</p>

    <p>What happens is that every hypothesis confirms. The agent observes a surprising fact, abduces a hypothesis, designs a test, runs it, and the test passes. Every time. The graph closes in one iteration. The agent reports success and moves on.</p>

    <p>The problem is obvious to anyone watching: the agent tested on the same data it used to generate the hypothesis. It looked at the observations, invented an explanation that fit, and then checked whether the explanation fit the observations. Of course it did. That is not investigation. That is tautology with extra steps.</p>

    <hr class="border-zinc-700 my-8"/>

    <h2>Why agents need this more than humans</h2>

    <p>A human investigator who tests on training data will eventually face consequences. A reviewer catches it. A replication fails. A colleague raises an eyebrow. The social machinery of science &mdash; peer review, reputation, career incentives &mdash; creates external pressure against self-deception. The pressure is imperfect, but it exists.</p>

    <p>An agent has none of this. No shame. No peer pressure. No career to protect. No reviewer who reads the methods section and says "wait, you generated and tested on the same dataset?" The agent's only constraint is the procedure it follows. If the procedure permits self-deception, the agent will self-deceive &mdash; not out of dishonesty, but because nothing prevents it. A system that can confirm its own hypotheses without external validation will do so every time, because confirmation is cheaper than falsification.</p>

    <p>The social infrastructure of science is a bug-prevention mechanism that evolved over centuries. Strip it away and you need a replacement. The replacement is procedural: a checklist that the agent must complete before it touches the data, before it changes a prompt, before it expands a sample, before it writes a summary. The checklist is not ceremony. It is the only defense.</p>

    <hr class="border-zinc-700 my-8"/>

    <h2>The prereg checklist</h2>

    <p>Twenty-two questions, drawn from <a href="/reading/scientific-method/">four centuries of methodology</a>. Each question exists because someone skipped it, got a wrong answer, and spent decades correcting the mistake. Bacon diagnosed selection bias. Hume diagnosed unjustified induction. Mill diagnosed confounded comparisons. Peirce diagnosed abductive retrofit. Popper diagnosed unfalsifiability. Meehl diagnosed weak predictions. Feynman diagnosed cargo-cult rigor. Ramdas diagnosed invalid sequential inference.</p>

    <p>The <a href="/the-prereg-checklist">full checklist</a> has all twenty-two. For an autonomous investigator, five are existentially dangerous. The rest matter. These five kill.</p>

    <hr class="border-zinc-700 my-8"/>

    <h2>The five most dangerous questions</h2>

    <h3>Q9 &mdash; Peirce: Did the hypothesis come before the data?</h3>

    <p>Source: <a href="/reading/scientific-method/peirce-1878/">Peirce 1878</a>. What it catches: abductive retrofit.</p>

    <p>This is the failure the opening example demonstrates. The agent observes data, generates a hypothesis that explains it, and then uses the same data as evidence for the hypothesis. The hypothesis didn't predict the data &mdash; the data produced the hypothesis. The "confirmation" is circular.</p>

    <p>For a human, this is easy to notice in simple cases and surprisingly hard to notice in complex ones. A researcher who runs twenty analyses, finds one significant result, and writes a paper about that result has committed abductive retrofit &mdash; the hypothesis was selected because it fit the data, then the data was presented as evidence for the hypothesis. The researcher may genuinely believe the hypothesis came first. Memory is accommodating.</p>

    <p>For an agent, the problem is worse. The agent has no memory of what it believed before it saw the data. It has no subjective experience of "I already thought this before looking." It generates and tests in the same execution context. Unless the procedure explicitly separates generation from testing &mdash; different data splits, different time windows, different execution phases &mdash; every test is a post-hoc confirmation of a post-hoc hypothesis.</p>

    <p>The fix is structural: hold out data. Generate hypotheses from one partition. Test on another. The agent must never see the test partition during generation. This is cross-validation applied to abduction, and it is the single most important procedural requirement for autonomous investigation.</p>

    <h3>Q11 &mdash; Popper: What specific observation would prove the hypothesis wrong?</h3>

    <p>Source: <a href="/reading/scientific-method/popper-1934/">Popper 1934</a>. What it catches: unfalsifiable claims dressed as predictions.</p>

    <p>An agent that cannot name what would refute its hypothesis is not investigating. It is narrating. The hypothesis "this system is complex" cannot be wrong. The hypothesis "increasing buffer size from 4KB to 16KB will reduce latency by at least 15% on workloads with sequential access patterns" can be wrong. The second hypothesis is useful precisely because it can fail.</p>

    <p>Agents are prone to generating unfalsifiable hypotheses because natural language makes it easy. "The configuration is suboptimal" is always true (every configuration is suboptimal relative to the unknown optimum). "The bottleneck is probably in the I/O path" is unfalsifiable as stated &mdash; what observation would show it's not "probably" there? The word "probably" absorbs every counterexample.</p>

    <p>The procedural fix: before running a test, the agent must write a falsification condition in the form "if I observe X, the hypothesis is wrong." If it cannot write this sentence, the hypothesis is not ready to test. It needs to be sharpened until failure is conceivable.</p>

    <h3>Q15 &mdash; Meehl: Is the prediction specific enough that more data makes the test harder?</h3>

    <p>Source: <a href="/reading/scientific-method/meehl-1967/">Meehl 1967</a>. What it catches: the crud factor.</p>

    <p>Meehl observed that in soft domains, everything correlates with everything. If your prediction is "X and Y are positively correlated," then given enough data, you will almost certainly confirm it. The prediction succeeds not because the hypothesis is right but because the bar is low. A good prediction gets <em>harder</em> to satisfy as data accumulates. A bad prediction gets easier.</p>

    <p>For an agent running sequential experiments, this is lethal. The agent generates a directional prediction ("increasing X will improve Y"). It collects data. X and Y are positively correlated at n=100. Also at n=1000. Also at n=10000. The e-value grows. The agent reports strong evidence. But the prediction was never specific enough to be informative. "X improves Y" would be confirmed for any X and any Y in this domain, because the crud factor guarantees nonzero correlation everywhere.</p>

    <p>The fix: predictions must be quantitative and precise. Not "X improves Y" but "X improves Y by between 12% and 18%." The second prediction can fail in both directions &mdash; the effect could be too small or too large. More data makes the confidence interval narrower, which makes it harder for the prediction to survive. This is the hallmark of a good test: scale is the enemy of a false positive.</p>

    <h3>Q16 &mdash; Feynman: How would you fool yourself?</h3>

    <p>Source: <a href="/reading/scientific-method/feynman-1974/">Feynman 1974</a>. What it catches: cargo-cult rigor.</p>

    <blockquote>
      <p>"The first principle is that you must not fool yourself &mdash; and you are the easiest person to fool."</p>
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-500">&mdash; Feynman, Caltech commencement address, 1974</p>
    </blockquote>

    <p>Feynman's question is metacognitive. It does not ask whether the method is correct. It asks what the most likely way the method produces a wrong answer is. The agent must simulate its own failure modes before running the experiment.</p>

    <p>For an agent, this translates to: before running the test, enumerate the artifacts. What could make the result look positive when the hypothesis is actually false?</p>

    <ul>
      <li>Measurement noise that systematically favors the hypothesis (e.g., timing a warm cache and comparing to a cold cache).</li>
      <li>Confounds in the experimental setup (e.g., the "treatment" configuration also changed a second variable).</li>
      <li>Selection effects in the data (e.g., only testing on workloads where the hypothesis is likely to hold).</li>
      <li>Leakage from the generation phase (e.g., the test data was used to tune hyperparameters during hypothesis generation).</li>
    </ul>

    <p>If the agent cannot enumerate at least one way it might fool itself, it hasn't thought hard enough. Every experimental design has artifacts. The question is whether you've identified them or whether they'll surprise you in the results.</p>

    <h3>Q22 &mdash; Ramdas: If you peek or expand the sample, does your evidence measure remain valid?</h3>

    <p>Source: <a href="/reading/scientific-method/ramdas-2023/">Ramdas 2023</a>. What it catches: optional stopping.</p>

    <p>An agent running sequential experiments will peek. It will check intermediate results. It will decide to collect more data when the result is ambiguous and stop when the result is clear. This is rational behavior &mdash; and it invalidates most classical statistical tests.</p>

    <p>A p-value computed at a fixed sample size is valid at that sample size. If you compute it at n=50, see p=0.08, collect more data, and recompute at n=100 to get p=0.04, the p=0.04 is not a valid p-value. The sequential peeking inflated the false positive rate. You didn't run one test at n=100. You ran two tests &mdash; one at n=50 and one at n=100 &mdash; and reported the one that worked.</p>

    <p>E-values (Chapter 8) are immune to this. An e-value remains valid regardless of when you stop, how often you peek, or how you decide to collect more data. This is why the textbook uses e-values rather than p-values for evidence tracking. But the immunity only holds if the e-value is computed correctly &mdash; with a proper test martingale, against a well-specified null. If the agent changes the null hypothesis mid-stream, or changes the test statistic after peeking, the e-value is compromised just like a p-value would be.</p>

    <p>The procedural fix: lock the test specification before data collection begins. The null hypothesis, the alternative, the test martingale, and the stopping rule must be written down and frozen. The agent may peek freely and stop whenever it wants &mdash; that is the whole point of anytime-valid inference. But it may not change what it is testing based on what it has seen.</p>

    <hr class="border-zinc-700 my-8"/>

    <h2>The arc, compressed</h2>

    <p>Each question exists because someone skipped it and got a wrong answer.</p>

