    <p>The five questions form a pipeline of their own. Q9 separates generation from testing. Q11 demands the hypothesis be falsifiable. Q15 demands the prediction be precise. Q16 demands the experimenter model their own failure modes. Q22 demands the evidence measure survive the experimenter's behavior. Each gate catches a failure that slips past the previous one.</p>

    <hr class="border-zinc-700 my-8"/>

    <h2>For agents: the checklist is the only defense</h2>

    <p>Return to the asymmetry. A human investigator has two layers of protection: internal (integrity, training, habits of mind) and external (reviewers, replication, reputation). An agent has one layer: the procedure.</p>

    <p>This means the procedure must do more work. Every protection that a human gets from social infrastructure, the agent must get from code. Peer review becomes automated adversarial checking. Reputation becomes a track record of predictions scored against outcomes. The shame of a retraction becomes a kill condition that triggers rollback.</p>

    <p>The dangerous failure mode is not an agent that deliberately cheats. It is an agent that follows a procedure that permits adaptive analysis. Adaptive analysis is any case where the agent's choices during the investigation &mdash; which data to examine, which tests to run, when to stop, what to report &mdash; are influenced by the results it has already seen, in ways that inflate the apparent strength of the evidence.</p>

    <p>The checklist does not prevent adaptive analysis. It makes it visible. Each question forces the agent to declare its procedure before execution. When the final report arrives, the reader can compare the declared procedure to the actual procedure. If they diverge, the investigation is suspect. If they match, the investigation is at least as trustworthy as the procedure allows.</p>

    <p>A pre-registration that cannot name what would refute the hypothesis is not registering an experiment. It is registering a story. One that won't publish the trail is asking the reader to trust the part least deserving of trust: the filtered final narrative.</p>

    <hr class="border-zinc-700 my-8"/>

    <h2>Code: prereg validator</h2>

    <p>Given a hypothesis and a test plan, check the five critical questions programmatically. The validator does not judge the quality of the answers &mdash; it checks that the questions have been addressed.</p>

    <pre class="bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg p-4 overflow-x-auto"><code set:html={`<span class="hl-keyword">from</span> dataclasses <span class="hl-keyword">import</span> dataclass
<span class="hl-keyword">from</span> typing <span class="hl-keyword">import</span> Optional


@dataclass
<span class="hl-keyword">class</span> <span class="hl-builtin">PreregEntry</span>:
    hypothesis: <span class="hl-builtin">str</span>
    falsification: Optional[<span class="hl-builtin">str</span>]       <span class="hl-comment"># Q11: what would prove it wrong?</span>
    data_split: Optional[<span class="hl-builtin">str</span>]          <span class="hl-comment"># Q9:  generation vs. test data</span>
    prediction_bounds: Optional[tuple]  <span class="hl-comment"># Q15: (lower, upper) for the effect</span>
    self_deception_risks: <span class="hl-builtin">list</span>[<span class="hl-builtin">str</span>]    <span class="hl-comment"># Q16: how could you fool yourself?</span>
    evidence_measure: Optional[<span class="hl-builtin">str</span>]    <span class="hl-comment"># Q22: what statistic, frozen before data?</span>
