    <p>The validator is intentionally minimal. It checks that each field is populated, not that the content is good. A falsification condition that says "if pigs fly" would pass. The validator catches the cases where the agent didn't even try to answer the question. Catching bad answers requires judgment; catching missing answers requires a null check.</p>

    <p>In practice, this is sufficient for the most common failure. The agent that tests on training data almost never declares "I am testing on training data." It simply omits the data-split field. The agent that generates unfalsifiable hypotheses doesn't write "this hypothesis is unfalsifiable." It leaves the falsification field empty. The null check catches the omission. Judging quality is a harder problem &mdash; and a human one, at least for now.</p>

    <hr class="border-zinc-700 my-8"/>

    <h2>The checklist in the loop</h2>

    <p>Where does the checklist sit in the architecture from chapters 8&ndash;11?</p>

    <p>The hypothesis graph has three phases: <strong>generate</strong> (abduce a hypothesis from a surprising observation), <strong>test</strong> (design and run an experiment), and <strong>update</strong> (classify the evidence trajectory and follow the edge). The checklist gates the transition from generate to test. No hypothesis crosses into the testing phase without passing the five questions.</p>

