            <td class="text-gray-400">E-values (anytime-valid). Kill conditions generate next edge.</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <p>The gate is the cheapest component in the pipeline. Filling out five fields takes seconds. The cost of skipping it is catastrophic: the entire downstream evidence trajectory is built on a foundation that may be circular, unfalsifiable, or imprecise. The e-values will compose correctly. The trajectory classification will run. The convergence criterion will fire. And the conclusion will be wrong, because the hypothesis was never properly separated from the data that generated it.</p>

    <p>Garbage in, mathematically valid garbage out.</p>

    <hr class="border-zinc-700 my-8"/>

    <h2>What this chapter does not solve</h2>

    <p>The checklist catches self-deception. It ensures the agent has separated generation from testing, named a falsification condition, specified prediction bounds, enumerated artifacts, and frozen the test specification. If the agent does all of this correctly, the investigation is sound.</p>

    <p>But what happens when the test fails?</p>

    <p>The agent has a hypothesis. It passes the checklist. It runs the experiment. The prediction is wrong &mdash; the effect is outside the bounds. The hypothesis is killed. The kill condition fires. A new edge appears in the hypothesis graph. The agent must now generate a new hypothesis.</p>

    <p>It generates one. It tries the same technique: induction. The technique doesn't work. It tries induction again, harder &mdash; larger sample, finer grid, more compute. Still doesn't work. It tries induction a third time. <a href="https://www.cambridge.org/core/books/mathematical-problem-solving/71E357D32C51F5B4BB279C244ACA6E2F">Schoenfeld (1985)</a> filmed exactly this pattern in human problem-solvers. He called it the wild goose chase: one technique, ridden to exhaustion, consuming the entire session. Novices and experts know the same techniques. The difference is control &mdash; knowing when to switch and what to switch to.</p>

    <p>The checklist has no answer for this. It can tell you whether your hypothesis is well-formed. It cannot tell you which technique to try when your current technique fails. It catches self-deception but not strategic paralysis. You need a manual that maps failure modes to alternative techniques &mdash; a lookup table from "this didn't work" to "try this instead."</p>

    <p>This is where proof enters methodeutics. Some claims can't be tested with fresh data &mdash; they require structural validation. "Is this the simplest explanation?" is not an empirical question. "Does the residual have structure?" is not an empirical question. These need the deductive edge of the triangle: given a claim, derive what must hold and check whether it does. The proof manual is that edge, systematized.</p>

    <p>Chapter 13.</p>

